column5:
Today was brutal. Many chapters of lessons from the book of horrors written today. Experiment with nutrition on race day, fail. Experiment with shoes, double fail. Sunburnt. A monster novice day. Paid the price for this stupidity hard! Managed to crawl home but barely within cut-off with an acute groin strain/torn adductor and a visit to the race doctor to stop shivering. Just happy to have finished. 
Found out afterwards I got into Hardrock 100 again next year - after today I might need to downgrade to a parkrun rather. 
Thanks for the help and support out there. It was a dark day 🙂
Feeling way happier with life, the universe and everything else after this bit of movement and some coffee 🤙🏼
When things just feel effortless, must be all the training last weekend :p

column5:
I finally caught up with my Strava goal for 2019... took a bit of splicing between the Garmin InReach and Fenix Data but it's mostly here... definitely not just 2,871 but 🤷‍♀️--- 

A very long, oxygen deprived trek through the Drakensberg. That pretty much sums up the past weekend. I’m incredibly thankful to have been able to finish the Drakensberg Grand Traverse technically unassisted and solo, but with @heleenmills on the other side of the satellite messenger, never alone. 
Sometimes it’s better not to overthink things so this was a pretty spontaneous, last minute decision to go back to the beautiful wild and remote Drakensberg for the Traverse. These type of decisions comes with a price and the lack of acclimatizing and associated suffering was the price I had to pay… No amount of beet root juice gives you a shortcut to running at altitude :) Like the Roger Alan Wade song goes “If Your Gonna Be Dumb, You Gotta Be Tough” (Listened to this bloody song quite a few times on the Traverse). This was an experience and memories that will last a lifetime. There’s a longer rambling write-up on my Facebook if you into that stuff but they say a few pictures is worth a 1000 words so here’s a few! 
It took 95 hours, with some storms, some sleep, some new Basotho friends and a whole lot of gels but I made it from the Sentinel Car Park to Bushman’s Nek Border Post. ~210km.

On the way tagged - 
Mont-aux-Sources (at 3,282m)
Cleft Peak (3,281 m)
Champagne Castle (3,377 m)
Mafadi (3,450 m) - South Africa’s Highest Point
Giant’s Castle (3,314 m)
Thabana Ntlenyana (3,482 m) - Southern African’s Highest Point 

#dgt2019 #drakensberg #mountainrunning #butnotreally #traverse #memories #onewildandpreciouslife

column3: Best described as a less popular interpretation of Turret Gully
column5:
You got to know when to hold 'em
Know when to fold 'em
Know when to walk away and know when to run.

--- 

A beautiful rainy run past Grootkop, followed by an hour of wet, slightly desperate, bush wacking trying to get to Eagle’s Nest before dark via what probably was not Turret Gully. It would be more truthful to say that my understanding of ‘Turret Ravine’ / Agatha’s Gully was probably severely flawed. It was based on cursory research, which went as far as getting a coordinate and winging it from there. Back to the books for this one 🤦‍♀️ 📚 

Had no aces on this route.

Hike up to Hoare Hutt. Followed by a ‘quick’ excursion with [strava://athletes/24547685/15]Frederik Gerner  to the Mostertshoek Twins, because it’ll only take us 1.5 hours… based on my vague recollection of the last mission up here, an estimation which was based on Waaihoek Peak… 🙈

But handheld bottles, a few jelly sweets and good spirits are all that’s needed for a great type 2 adventure. Well that’s all that’s needed for the first 4 hours, then you really need water. Sanity prevailed and the rare sane decision made to turn around despite it feeling like it’s “just another 30 minutes” to the summit. 

“Gotta have faith” - George Michael delivered I the form of a tiny puddle, with some of the sweetest water ever tasted. 

5.5 hours later… happy times and reunited with the rest at Hoare Hutt, and the most spectacular sunset from Waaihoek. Sadly also with a box seat for the fires near Rawsonville. 

Magical weekend. Thanks [strava://athletes/1464695/11]Henty Waker ✊🏽

Gutted for my team mate @kirrabalmanno who injured her ankle and had to make the very difficult decision to withdraw from this year’s PTL.   I know how much this race meant to you, and how much heart you put into this. So thankful to have gotten to spend a small part of this wild and precious journey with you. 

There will be another year, another chance to do this. I’m sure now that you’ve had a taste for the PTL we’ll see you here helmet in hand again.   For me, obviously also very disappointed as well that things had to end this way. The PTL is about the team, which is one of the most wonderful aspects of this beautiful and brutal journey. It also means we start and finish as a team, an experience we’ll get to share on another time 🧡.   I’m looking forward to spending a days in these wild mountains exploring the sections of the route that we missed out, so I can take some photos for Kirra.   Heal up quickly my friend, and a big thanks for letting me share this journey with you. ✨🍀
